abstract: As the South Carolina primary unfolds Saturday, Bernie Sanders won’t be hustling for last-minute votes in Charleston or courting party elders in the state capital of Columbia. Rather, he'll be invading Elizabeth Warren’s home turf.

headline_main: Sanders Makes Bold Play to Win Primary on Warren’s Home Turf

abstract: In a state where elections and litigation are intertwined, add this to Florida's ballot box saga: A pair of Floridians are asking a court to remove Sen. Bernie Sanders, the Democratic front-runner for president, from the state's March 17 primary ballot.
snippet: In a state where elections and litigation are intertwined, add this to Florida's ballot box saga: A pair of Floridians are asking a court to remove Sen. Bernie Sanders, the Democratic front-runner for president, from the state's March 17 primary b...
lead_paragraph: TALLAHASSEE, Fla. — In a state where elections and litigation are intertwined, add this to Florida's ballot box saga: A pair of Floridians are asking a court to remove Sen. Bernie Sanders, the Democratic front-runner for president, from the state's March 17 primary ballot.
headline_main: Florida Lawsuit Questions Sanders' Democratic Bona Fides
headline_print_headline: Florida Lawsuit Questions Sanders' Democratic Bona Fides

abstract: Nervous Democrats who never thought Bernie Sanders had a chance of winning the 2020 presidential primary are now asking the party's big-dollar donors to open their wallets to stop the self-described democratic socialist.

abstract: Senate Democrats on Tuesday blocked a pair of Republican bills that would ban most late-term abortions and threaten prison for doctors who don't try saving the life of infants born alive during abortions.

abstract: U.S. Senator Bernie Sanders has widened his lead for the Democratic presidential nomination and overtaken Joe Biden in support among African Americans - a voting bloc that until now has largely favored the former vice president, according to a Reuters/Ipsos national poll released on Tuesday.
snippet: U.S. Senator Bernie Sanders has widened his lead for the Democratic presidential nomination and overtaken Joe Biden in support among African Americans - a voting bloc that until now has largely favored the former vice president, according to a Reu...
lead_paragraph: NEW YORK — U.S. Senator Bernie Sanders has widened his lead for the Democratic presidential nomination and overtaken Joe Biden in support among African Americans - a voting bloc that until now has largely favored the former vice president, according to a Reuters/Ipsos national poll released on Tuesday.
headline_main: Sanders Surpasses Biden Among African American Voters: Reuters/Ipsos Poll
headline_print_headline: Sanders Surpasses Biden Among African American Voters: Reuters/Ipsos Poll

lead_paragraph: For all the talk since 2016 of foreign election interference and Russian “meddling,” it seems few people really understand the information war and how not to play into the hands of our enemies. Last week is proof.

headline_main: Russia Wants to Meddle in Our Election. We’re Helping.

abstract: Experiences in Washington State and Colorado demonstrate the challenges of trying to create a nationwide insurance plan.
snippet: Experiences in Washington State and Colorado demonstrate the challenges of trying to create a nationwide insurance plan.
lead_paragraph: Government insurance advocates who are skeptical of Medicare for All’s prospects are placing their hopes on the “public option” as an easier-to-enact step in the same direction. All of the leading competitors to Bernie Sanders, who remains unyielding in his commitment to single-payer health care, have embraced some version of what Pete Buttigieg calls “Medicare for all who want it.”

abstract: President Donald Trump suggested on Tuesday that Democrats who don't want Bernie Sanders to win their party's presidential nomination tried to hurt the senator's chances by leaking information about Russian activities promoting his campaign. Trump gave no evidence for his claim.

lead_paragraph: NEW DELHI — President Donald Trump suggested on Tuesday that Democrats who don't want Bernie Sanders to win their party's presidential nomination tried to hurt the senator's chances by leaking information about Russian activities promoting his campaign. Trump gave no evidence for his claim.
headline_main: Trump Says Without Evidence Dems Leak Intel to Hurt Sanders
headline_print_headline: Trump Says Without Evidence Dems Leak Intel to Hurt Sanders
